    </div>

    <p>
      Alright I've been kind of losing my tourist steam, but I went all in for Dia de Muertos here in Mexico. Day of the dead, aka Día de Muertos here is not just Mexican Halloween; it's an Aztec tradition of honoring the dead and setting up ofrendas (offerings) for loved ones who are making the journey back from the dead and a time for honoring and remembering the dead.
    </p>
    <p>
      Have you seen Coco? If not: shut up, stop reading this, quit your job and go watch Coco. I'll wait.
    </p>
    <p>Welcome back!</p>
    </p>
    <p>
      So Día de Muertos is usually a family holiday: you build the ofrenda at home with items that were of meaning to the deceased, some food (because they're hungry and you're Mexican and you need to give food to absolutely everyone), some photos, marigolds, candles to light the way, sugar skull candy and kind of whatever else you think fits. It's cool because it's pretty personalized. To whomever has the honor(?) of building my ofrenda; I want Twizzlers, hot wings and/or Chilaquiles, peanut M&M's, some fire memes and maybe an Indio beer.  Here's some of the Ofrendas that were out in Puebla:
    </p>
  </div>
