    <p>
      They also have a Catrinas parade (the skeleton ladies) and an all encompassing Día de Muertos parade (true story: they have that parade because a James Bond movie showed it and tourists started expecting there to be one so the city obliged. Colorado bought some buffalo to put next to the airport so people would like it more...and then replaced it with <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blue_Mustang" target="_blank" rel="noopener">this evil blue horse</a> that literally killed its maker. Judge away, but judge fairly.)
    </p>


    <p>
      I saw zero parades, so there's room for growth next time.
    </p>
    <p>
      Instead, I went to Xochilmilco which I've been meaning to see for a long time. Mexico City was originally entirely a system of swampy canals with zero roads. The Spaniards came and paved over the lake, which was a great idea and now Mexico City is literally sinking...fun! So Xochimilco is the only part of the city that's still the original canal system. I went to another show on the water in Xochimilco (I hope I'm done typing that now, it's hard). This one was a take on the legend of La Llorona. La Llorona is a lady who, according to the legend, comes when kids cry too much to...idk take or eat or kill them. In this play la llorona was an Aztec princess who was impregnated by a conquistador and then the Spanish murdered absolutely everyone and the end. She never gets revenge. Just bothers sad kids.
    </p>
    <p>
      I've noticed that Mexicans don't really seem to expect that the good guys will win in some capacity. When I went to Lucha Libre the bad guys won EVERY SINGLE MATCH and then it ended and that's just how it is. The bad guys win. I kind of wonder if they're being conditioned for a corrupt government at a young age. Or maybe it's a weird Americanism that I expect the hero/underdog to have a comeback at some point and things to have at least some kind of happy ending. La Llorana left me expecting a third act where she comes back and slaughters some conquistadors, but I guess we all know that didn't happen. No use in pretending otherwise. She could at least hand out some kidney stones, though.
    </p>
    <p>
      I'd call my first Día de Muertos a success? I like the idea of taking the time for your loved ones to build them an ofrenda with stuff they would like and I also like the idea of it not being an entirely sad thing. It's a better idea than my grandpa's of turning the dead into crackers. Sorry to rank cultures, but I'm not eating my dead relatives. Of course I want you all to think of me and put out a lot of Twizzlers and Sour Patch Kids, but  my love for little kid candy is a small part of my personality, so make sure you try to capture my awkwardness, inappropriate sarcasm and the number of hours I accidentally spent hate-watching The Hills like 10 years after it originally aired.
    </p>
    <p>
      Wise little readers would point out that I said my next post will be about coding and this isn't about coding. Very wise, little reader. Maybe the next post. I started writing it and it turned into a lot. Trying to trim it down. Go watch Coco again.
    </p>
